data.sampled:
The name of the option strategy being implemented in the example is a bull put spread. It is a combination of selling a put option at a higher strike price and purchasing a put option at a lower strike price. The trade involves purchasing an option with a lower premium and selling an option with a higher premium, which gives the trade a credit position.

The bull put spread is used when investors expect the stock price to stay above the sold put's striking price. By selling the higher strike price put and buying the lower strike price put with a credit, the investor hopes to profit from the credit received for the trade. As long as the stock price stays above the sold put's striking price, the investor keeps the credit received as profit.
